      <hedline>
        <hl1>Among the Mooks</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dave Alpert letter on R J Smith's August 6 article holds popularity of rap, wrestling and pornography shows growing anger and cynicism among working and middle-class America (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The popularity of rap, rap-metal, wrestling and pornography evidence a growing anger and cynicism among the young and not-so-young of working- and middle-class America. But why stop there? What about Letterman, Seinfeld, ''Sex and the City'' and any number of upscale advertising campaigns that evidence a growing hostility closer to home?</p>
        <p>Is it enough to sit clucking our tongues at the unwashed hordes, or should we take a closer look at ourselves and try to understand our own unease during what, according to Wall Street and the news media, are the best of times?</p>
        <p>Dave Alpert  New York</p>
      </block>
